_failures | group_by(.project, .language) | map({k:[.[0].project,.[0].language], n:length})'\n```\n\n## Observed\n\n| Project | Language | Collisions |\n|---|---|---|\n| remix | TypeScript | 57 |\n| flask | Python | 26 |\n| remix | TSX | 22 |\n| remix | Markdown | 5 |\n| ripgrep | Rust | 3 |\n| gh-cli | Markdown | 2 |\n| tf-aws-vpc | Markdown | 1 |\n| **TOTAL** | | **116** |\n\n## Repeatable patterns (not random)\n\n**Python (flask)** — nested `def` inside multiple test functions reuses simple names without scoping. The regex extractor produces the same qualified name for each:\n\n```\ntests/test_appctx.py:        qualified_name \"tests.test_appctx.index\" appears 5 times\ntests/test_helpers.py:       qualified_name \"tests.test_helpers.TestUrlFor.index\" appears 4 times\nsrc/flask/config.py:         qualified_name \"src.flask.config.ConfigAttribute.__get__\" appears 3 times\n```\n\nThe Python regex extractor doesn't track lexical scope, so all five `def index(...)` inside different `def test_X(...)` collide. Four of the five are silently dropped.\n\n**TypeScript (remix)** — file-default-export with the same name as the file:\n\n```\ntemplate/app/middleware/render.tsx:  qualified_name \"template.app.middleware.render.render\" appears 2 times\n```\n\nThe `.tsx` file declares both `function render(...)` and `export default render`, and the regex extractor treats them as separate symbol candidates with identical qualified names.\n\n**Markdown** — identical heading text in different sections:\n\n```\ndocs/source.md:  qualified_name \"installation_from_source.windows\" appears 2 times\n```\n\nTwo `## Windows` subsections under different parent `# Installation from source` blocks. The QN strategy joins parent+child but doesn't disambiguate sibling order.\n\n**Rust (ripgrep)** — `#[cfg(...)]`-gated function variants with identical signatures:\n\n```\ncrates/ignore/src/pathutil.rs:  qualified_name \"crates::ignore::src::pathutil::is_hidden\" appears 3 times\n```\n\nThree `fn is_hidden(...)` bodies behind different `#[cfg(unix)]` / `#[cfg(windows)]` / `#[cfg(target_os = ...)]` predicates. The regex extractor strips cfg gates, leaving three identical qualified names.\n\n## Why this matters\n\nCLAUDE.md is explicit: \"a PR that bumps a count from 0 to N is a regression by default — reviewers should treat any snapshot diff that adds a non-zero failure entry as a bug to fix, not a baseline to update.\" That gate exists because `qualified_name_collision` is a silent extractor bug — the user gets a smaller knowledge graph than they think they have. 116 instances at HEAD means the repos that *aren't* in the pinned-corpus snapshot suite are landing live regressions; they're just invisible until someone runs `pincher doctor`.\n\n## Suggested fixes (per pattern)\n\n1. **Python nested-scope** — extend the Python QN to include enclosing function name when nesting depth > 1. Cheap fix: track open `def` indentation in the regex pass, append `.<outer-fn>` to the QN when nested. Catches the test fixture / helper case.\n\n2. **TS default-export collision** — when a file ends in `export default <name>` and `<name>` is already in the file's symbol set, append `.default` to the second occurrence (or drop the wrapper).\n\n3. **Markdown sibling disambiguation** — append `.<idx>` to duplicate headings in the same parent. Loses round-trip readability of the QN but stops the silent drop.\n\n4. **Rust `#[cfg]` variants** — easier to fix: include the next non-comment line above `fn` in the QN when it starts with `#[cfg`. Or accept that platform-gated overloads are fundamentally one symbol.\n\n5. **Diagnostics already in place** — `pincher doctor` already surfaces these. What's missing is a knob like `--strict-collisions` that fails indexing or returns non-zero exit, useful for CI integration. The existing snapshot gate covers pinned corpora; this would cover ad-hoc projects.\n\n## Environment\n\nPincher master @ `de076eff`. All 6 corpora freshly indexed with `--data-dir /d/research/data` on 2026-05-08; failures captured via `pincher doctor --json --top 200`.\n","reactions":{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kwad77/pincher/issues/115/reactions","total_count":0,"+1":0,"-1":0,"laugh":0,"hooray":0,"confused":0,"heart":0,"rocket":0,"eyes":0},"timeline_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kwad77/pincher/issues/115/timeline","performed_via_github_app":null,"state_reason":"completed","pinned_comment":null,"score":1.0},{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Takazudo/zudo-front-builder/issues/401","repository_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Takazudo/zudo-front-builder","labels_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Takazudo/zudo-front-builder/issues/401/labels{/name}","comments_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Takazudo/zudo-front-builder/issues/401/comments","events_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Takazudo/zudo-front-builder/issues/401/events","html_url":"https://github.com/Takazudo/zudo-front-builder/issues/401","id":4505083762,"node_id":"I_kwDOSMh-vc8AAAABDIYfcg","number":401,"title":"[Concepts Runtime Pages][Sub] Write \"SSR on a Worker (adapter mode)\" Concepts page","user":{"login":"Takazudo","id":128233,"node_id":"MDQ6VXNlcjEyODIzMw==","avatar_url":"https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/128233?v=4","gravatar_id":"","url":"https://api.github.com/users/Takazudo","html_url":"https://github.com/Takazudo","followers_url":"https://api.github.com/users/Takazudo/followers","following_url":"https://api.github.com/users/Takazudo/following{/other_user}","gists_url":"https://api.github.com/users/Takazudo/gists{/gist_id}","starred_url":"https://api.github.com/users/Takazudo/starred{/owner}{/repo}","subscriptions_url":"https://api.github.com/users/Takazudo/subscriptions","organizations_url":"https://api.github.com/users/Takazudo/orgs","repos_url":"https://api.github.com/users/Takazudo/repos","events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/Takazudo/events{/privacy}","received_events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/Takazudo/received_events","type":"User","user_view_type":"public","site_admin":false},"labels":[{"id":10789146042,"node_id":"LA_kwDOSMh-vc8AAAACgxVNug","url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Takazudo/zudo-front-builder/labels/sub","name":"sub","color":"0E8A16","default":false,"description":"Big-plan sub-task under an epic"}],"state":"closed","locked":false,"assignees":[],"milestone":null,"comments":1,"created_at":"2026-05-22T19:18:25Z","updated_at":"2026-05-22T20:21:55Z","closed_at":"2026-05-22T20:21:55Z","assignee":null,"author_association":"OWNER","active_lock_reason":null,"sub_issues_summary":{"total":0,"completed":0,"percent_completed":0},"issue_dependencies_summary":{"blocked_by":0,"total_blocked_by":0,"blocking":0,"total_blocking":0},"body":"- https://github.com/Takazudo/zudo-front-builder/issues/399\n\n---\n\n**Wave:** 1\n**Execution mode:** subagents — independent self-contained Concepts page; no coordination needed\n**Model:** sonnet — English technical documentation with a comparison callout; scope and structure fully specified\n\n## What needs to be done\n\nWrite a new Concepts page that explains the production deploy story for `prerender = false` zfb pages — what the build emits, how requests are dispatched, and how `getCloudflareContext()` actually works. The framing is \"your page handler is just `async (req) => Response`; honestly, it's just a Cloudflare Worker, with one DX-flavored ALS trick.\" Include an embedded \"If you know Next.js / Remix\" comparison callout.\n\n**File to create:** `docs/src/content/docs/concepts/ssr-on-a-worker.mdx`\n\n## Files to read first (reference material)\n\n- `docs/src/content/docs/concepts/architecture-overview.mdx` — voice + `<Info>` patterns + the \"two bundles\" framing that this page extends\n- `docs/src/content/docs/guides/ssr-and-cloudflare-bindings.mdx` — **must read in full**; the new page complements the guide and must explicitly cross-link to it. Do NOT duplicate the \"how to set up `wrangler.toml` / D1 / secrets\" content.\n- `docs/src/content/docs/concepts/islands.mdx` — `\"use client\"` islands are a separate browser-side bundle, not part of the worker output\n- `docs/src/content/docs/architecture/js-runtime.mdx` — optional cross-link target; aligns dev-mode embedded V8 wording with prod-mode V8 isolate wording. Keep terminology consistent.\n- `docs/CLAUDE.md` — frontmatter conventions, admonitions, no h1\n- The `zfb-example-webshop` sibling project (`$HOME/repos/zfb-ex/zfb-example-webshop`) — use it as a *generic* reference; do **NOT** mention \"webshop\" or \"Driftwood\" or any project-specific identifier in the published page. Generic phrasing like \"a page handler in an adapter-mode project\" is fine.\n- **`packages/zfb-adapter-cloudflare/src/worker-wrapper.mjs`** — the **authoritative** source for the auto-generated `_worker.js` shape: ASSETS-first dispatch, `AsyncLocalStorage` storage-key registration under `globalThis`, GET/HEAD probe vs POST/PUT/PATCH/DELETE routing. The published `dist/_worker.js` is generated *from* this file.\n- **`packages/zfb-adapter-cloudflare/src/index.ts`** — the user-facing `getCloudflareContext<Env>()` implementation; this is the matching side of the ALS dance the wrapper sets up.\n- **`packages/zfb-adapter-cloudflare/src/build.ts`** (optional) — the build-time hook that emits the two-layer output. Useful for verifying the \"what the build emits\" section is accurate.\n- `packages/zfb-adapter-cloudflare/README.md` — keep the new Concepts page's framing aligned with the README's wording so package docs and site docs don't drift.\n- For the auto-generated `_worker.js` header: paraphrase the contract — Cloudflare Pages Advanced Mode + ASSETS-first dispatch + ALS storage-key. Do NOT paste the entire generated file. **Do NOT** pin to a specific line count (e.g. \"~70 lines\") — the file is generated and that number can rot. Use \"a small auto-generated stub\" framing.\n\n## Page structure (required sections)\n\n1. **Frontmatter:**\n\n```\n---\ntitle: SSR on a Worker (adapter mode)\ndescription: \"How a prerender = false zfb page actually runs in production — the two-layer worker output, the ASSETS-first dispatch, and the AsyncLocalStorage trick behind getCloudflareContext().\"\nsidebar_position: 8\ncategory: Concepts\n---\n```\n\n2. **`<Info title=\"What this page covers\">`** — orientation; explicitly point to `guides/ssr-and-cloudflare-bindings.mdx` for \"how to actually set it up\" and frame this page as \"the mental model of what's running.\"\n\n3. **Your page is just a function** — open with the demystifying framing: a `prerender = false` page is an `async function (): Promise<Response>` that reads `getCloudflareContext()`, awaits its data, and returns a `Response`. Forms `POST` back to the same file; the handler branches on `request.method === \"POST\"`. Show a 10-line generic example (NOT webshop code — invent a generic `pages/account.tsx`-style sketch with `getUser(env, request)` and a form submit).\n\n4. **What the build actually emits** — the two-layer output:\n   - `dist/_worker.js` — a small auto-generated stub from `@takazudo/zfb-adapter-cloudflare`. Cloudflare Pages Advanced Mode entry: sets up `AsyncLocalStorage` under a stable `globalThis` key, dispatches every request.\n   - `dist/_zfb_inner.mjs` — the bundled Hono app with every `pages/*.tsx`, layouts, components, lib helpers compiled in. The \"real\" application bundle.\n   - Cross-link to `concepts/architecture-overview.mdx` for the \"two bundles\" mental model.\n\n5. **The dispatch flow** — table or numbered list:\n   - GET/HEAD → probe `env.ASSETS` first → 200 returns the static asset; 404 falls through to the inner Hono worker\n   - POST/PUT/PATCH/DELETE → skip ASSETS, go straight to the inner worker (form submissions, JSON APIs)\n   - Frame as \"static-first, dynamic-second — your static pages are not paying the SSR cost.\"\n\n6. **The `getCloudflareContext()` trick** — explain the `AsyncLocalStorage` mechanism:\n   - The outer `_worker.js` wraps `inner.fetch(request)` in `als.run({env, ctx, request}, …)`\n   - User code calls `getCloudflareContext<Env>()`; it pulls the stored value out of the ALS instance under the same `globalThis` key\n   - This is why `compatibility_flags = [\"nodejs_compat\"]` is **mandatory** — `AsyncLocalStorage` lives in `node:async_hooks`. Without it, the Worker fails at boot.\n   - Why ALS rather than prop-drilling: page handlers compose layouts and helpers freely; threading `env` as a parameter would force every component to know about it.\n\n7. **`<Info title=\"If you know Next.js or Remix\">`** — concept-mapping table:\n\n| Concept | Next.js App Router | Remix | zfb adapter-mode |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| File-based routing | `app/cart/page.tsx` | `routes/cart.tsx` | `pages/cart.tsx` |\n| Server data fetch | `async function Page()` | `loader` | `async function CartPage()` |\n| Mutation | Server Actions | `action` | Plain `<form method=\"post\">` |\n| Layouts | `layout.tsx` | nested route layouts | `layouts/*.tsx` (imported) |\n| Static vs dynamic | `dynamic = 'force-static'/'force-dynamic'` | (always dynamic) | `export const prerender = true/false` |\n\nPlus one short paragraph: \"Mechanically a Worker; ergonomically App-Router-style SSR; philosophically Remix-without-the-Remix-runtime. No RSC streaming, no Server Actions abstraction — just one bundle and a Web `fetch` handler.\"\n\n8. **What's NOT in the worker output** — short clarifier:\n   - `\"use client\"` islands are bundled separately (browser-shipped). Worker output does not contain them.\n   - Pages with `prerender = true` are pre-rendered to static HTML at build time and served by `env.ASSETS` — they never hit the worker.\n   - Cross-link to `concepts/islands.mdx`.\n\n9. **Related** — \"See also\" linking to: `concepts/architecture-overview.mdx`, `concepts/islands.mdx`, `guides/ssr-and-cloudflare-bindings.mdx` (explicit \"for hands-on setup, see the guide\" framing).\n\n## Acceptance criteria\n\n- File exists at `docs/src/content/docs/concepts/ssr-on-a-worker.mdx` with exact frontmatter shape (`sidebar_position: 8`)\n- All required sections present in roughly the order above\n- No h1 in the body — first heading is h2\n- Opening uses `<Info>` for orientation; framework-comparison block uses `<Info title=\"If you know Next.js or Remix\">`\n- The 10-line generic page-handler example uses **invented generic identifiers** (`getUser`, `account.tsx`, etc.) — no \"webshop\", \"Driftwood\", \"cart\", or any other identifier from `zfb-example-webshop`\n- Explicit cross-link to `guides/ssr-and-cloudflare-bindings.mdx` near the top with \"this page is the mental model; that page is the setup\" framing\n- **Lead with the user-facing story.** Package / crate / file paths appear as supporting evidence inline — narrative structure is \"your page is just a function\" → \"what the build emits\" → \"how it dispatches\", NOT \"here are the relevant files\".\n- Next.js / Remix comparison table appears as specified\n- **No \"~70 lines\" or other pinned generated-code metrics** — use \"small auto-generated stub\" / \"thin generated entry\" framing.\n- `pnpm --filter docs check` AND `pnpm --filter docs build` both pass from the repo root\n- **Japanese mirror NOT required** for this PR\n- Self-review at the end of writing: re-read as a first-day Next.js developer; the page should answer \"what is actually running in production?\" without sending you to the source code\n\n**Base branch:** `base/concepts-runtime-pages` — PR targets this branch (which itself targets `main`).","reactions":{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Takazudo/zudo-front-builder/issues/401/reactions","total_count":0,"+1":0,"-1":0,"laugh":0,"hooray":0,"confused":0,"heart":0,"rocket":0,"eyes":0},"timeline_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Takazudo/zudo-front-builder/issues/401/timeline","performed_via_github_app":null,"state_reason":"completed","pinned_comment":null,"score":1.0},{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/remix-run/remix/issues/11339","repository_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/remix-run/remix","labels_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/remix-run/remix/issues/11339/labels{/name}","comments_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/remix-run/remix/issues/11339/comments","events_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/remix-run/remix/issues/11339/events","html_url":"https://github.com/remix-run/remix/issues/11339","id":4371177887,"node_id":"I_kwDOElPqBM8AAAABBIrhnw","number":11339,"title":"Restore lazy typed header property accessors with standards-compliant SuperHeaders","user":{"login":"mjackson","id":92839,"node_id":"MDQ6VXNlcjkyODM5","avatar_url":"https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/92839?v=4","gravatar_id":"","url":"https://api.github.com/users/mjackson","html_url":"https://github.com/mjackson","followers_url":"https://api.github.com/users/mjackson/followers","following_url":"https://api.github.com/users/mjackson/following{/other_user}","gists_url":"https://api.github.com/users/mjackson/gists{/gist_id}","starred_url":"https://api.github.com/users/mjackson/starred{/owner}{/repo}","subscriptions_url":"https://api.github.com/users/mjackson/subscriptions","organizations_url":"https://api.github.com/users/mjackson/orgs","repos_url":"https://api.github.com/users/mjackson/repos","events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/mjackson/events{/privacy}","received_events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/mjackson/received_events","type":"User","user_view_type":"public","site_admin":false},"labels":[],"state":"closed","locked":false,"assignees":[],"milestone":null,"comments":0,"created_at":"2026-05-03T07:33:15Z","updated_at":"2026-05-03T17:26:00Z","closed_at":"2026-05-03T09:34:57Z","assignee":null,"author_association":"MEMBER","issue_field_values":[],"type":{"id":12246456,"node_id":"IT_kwDOA9QnQM4Aut24","name":"Feature","description":"A request, idea, or new functionality","color":"blue","created_at":"2024-02-04T15:03:37Z","updated_at":"2024-10-08T16:44:21Z","is_enabled":true},"active_lock_reason":null,"sub_issues_summary":{"total":0,"completed":0,"percent_completed":0},"issue_dependencies_summary":{"blocked_by":0,"total_blocked_by":0,"blocking":0,"total_blocking":0},"body":"## Summary\n\n`@remix-run/headers` used to expose a `SuperHeaders` class with convenient typed property accessors, e.g.\n\n```ts\nimport Headers from '@remix-run/headers'\n\nlet headers = new Headers(request.headers)\nlet mediaType = headers.contentType.mediaType\n\nheaders.contentType = { mediaType: 'text/html', charset: 'utf-8' }\nheaders.cacheControl.maxAge = 3600\nheaders.setCookie.push({ name: 'theme', value: 'dark', path: '/' })\n```\n\nThat API was removed because `SuperHeaders` was not keeping the native `Headers` internal storage in sync. It extended `Headers`, but the actual data lived in a separate private map. That broke runtimes like Bun where `Response` reads native `Headers` storage directly instead of going through overridden JavaScript methods.\n\nThis issue proposes restoring the old ergonomic property accessor behavior in a standards-compliant, performant, lazy, and type-safe way.\n\n## Historical context\n\nRelevant history:\n\n- Initial `SuperHeaders` implementation: https://github.com/remix-run/remix/commit/4d425a746e0de3a97ae87ef313a997e54b6a493b\n- Initial source file at that SHA: https://github.com/remix-run/remix/blob/4d425a746e0de3a97ae87ef313a997e54b6a493b/src/lib/super-headers.ts\n- Commit that made `SuperHeaders` extend native `Headers`: https://github.com/remix-run/remix/commit/5e69ad44815d6caca31e55029641554a57d721dd\n- Last version before removal: https://github.com/remix-run/remix/blob/f5035b2362dc9f8de2bad2a44a317c053a0ef578/packages/headers/src/lib/super-headers.ts\n- Old README showing the property accessor API: https://github.com/remix-run/remix/blob/f5035b2362dc9f8de2bad2a44a317c053a0ef578/packages/headers/README.md\n- Removal commit: https://github.com/remix-run/remix/commit/42fab9038df274daf65f3a17fb92e4b108c31846\n- Removal PR: https://github.com/remix-run/remix/pull/10911\n- Bun compatibility issue that exposed the storage problem: https://github.com/remix-run/remix/issues/10872\n- Simple native-sync attempt: https://github.com/remix-run/remix/pull/10889\n- More complete WIP exploration with mutation tracking/proxy ideas: https://github.com/remix-run/remix/pull/10904\n\n## Decisions\n\n- Export the class as a named `SuperHeaders` export and as the package default export.\n- Since `@remix-run/headers` currently has no default export, adding `SuperHeaders` as the default export should not break current users.\n- Do not support parsing a whole raw HTTP header string in the `SuperHeaders` constructor. Whole-header-string parsing should stay in `parse()`.\n- Support property initializer objects in the constructor.\n- Prefer as many typed accessors as possible, ideally one accessor for every known HTTP header. Use data-driven runtime descriptor definitions plus a TypeScript interface/declaration surface so we avoid one-off implementation code for every header while preserving type-safe properties.\n- Keep `ContentType` as-is. Use `headers.contentType.mediaType`; do not add `type`/`subtype` accessors as part of this work.\n- Mutating a typed object returned for a missing header should create the corresponding native header once the object serializes to a non-empty string.\n- Mutating a stale typed object should be a silent no-op. It must not overwrite newer native header state.\n- Preserve native `Headers` iteration and casing behavior as much as the runtime provides. Do not restore custom canonical ordering or custom iteration semantics.\n- Keep raw stringification in the existing `stringify(headers)` utility. Do not restore `SuperHeaders#toString()` as a separate raw-header formatter in this work.\n- Bun compatibility is a hard acceptance criterion.\n- The implementing PR should include tests, README updates, and a change file.\n\n## Goals\n\n- Restore convenient typed property accessors on a `SuperHeaders` class.\n- Preserve `instanceof Headers` by making the class a real `Headers` subclass.\n- Keep native `Headers` storage as the source of truth.\n- Avoid parsing header values until a typed accessor is actually read.\n- Keep setters ergonomic and rich, supporting strings, typed init objects, numbers, dates, arrays, and nullish deletion where appropriate.\n- Ensure mutations made through typed objects sync back to native `Headers` storage when the typed object is current.\n- Keep the public API type-safe, with explicit accessor types instead of a broad index signature.\n- Keep the implementation small enough to maintain by using descriptor tables and `Proxy` for parsed value mutation tracking.\n\n## Non-goals\n\n- Do not reintroduce a separate private map as the authoritative header store.\n- Do not proxy the `SuperHeaders` instance itself. Native `Headers` methods rely on internal slots, and a direct `Proxy` around a `Headers` instance can break methods like `get()` in Node unless every method is carefully rebound. A real subclass is safer.\n- Do not parse all known headers in the constructor.\n- Do not parse string setter values unless a typed getter is later read.\n- Do not add new parser classes for every HTTP header in the registry just to complete the accessor list. For headers without a structured parser, use typed scalar accessors (`string`, `number`, `Date`, etc.) where appropriate.\n\n## Proposed design\n\nAdd a real subclass:\n\n```ts\nexport class SuperHeaders extends Headers {\n  // Native Headers storage is authoritative.\n}\n```\n\nExport it from `packages/headers/src/index.ts`:\n\n```ts\nexport { type SuperHeadersInit, SuperHeaders, SuperHeaders as default } from './lib/super-headers.ts'\n```\n\nNative `Headers` methods remain standard. `SuperHeaders` should call `Headers.prototype.set`, `Headers.prototype.append`, and `Headers.prototype.delete` for standard operations and only use private state for a parsed-value cache.\n\n### Constructor behavior\n\nSupport standard `HeadersInit`-style inputs plus property initializer objects:\n\n```ts\nnew SuperHeaders()\nnew SuperHeaders(existingHeaders)\nnew SuperHeaders([['Content-Type', 'text/html']])\nnew SuperHeaders({ 'Content-Type': 'text/html' })\nnew SuperHeaders({ contentType: { mediaType: 'text/html', charset: 'utf-8' } })\n```\n\nDo not support this form:\n\n```ts\nnew SuperHeaders('Content-Type: text/html\\r\\nCache-Control: no-cache')\n```\n\nUse `parse(rawHeaders)` for whole-header-string parsing.\n\nFor plain object init, if an own property matches a typed accessor descriptor, route through the property setter. Otherwise, set the property name as a normal header name using native `Headers` behavior after converting the value to a string.\n\n### Lazy typed getters\n\nTyped getters parse on first access only:\n\n```ts\nlet headers = new SuperHeaders({ 'Content-Type': 'text/html' })\n\nheaders.has('Content-Type') // true, no typed parse\nheaders.get('Content-Type') // 'text/html', no typed parse\n\nlet contentType = headers.contentType // parse now\n```\n\nAccessing an absent typed object should return an empty header value object without immediately setting native storage:\n\n```ts\nlet headers = new SuperHeaders()\nlet contentType = headers.contentType\n\nheaders.has('Content-Type') // false\nheaders.get('Content-Type') // null\nString(contentType) // ''\n```\n\nMutating that returned object should create the native header once the object serializes to a non-empty string:\n\n```ts\nlet headers = new SuperHeaders()\nheaders.contentType.mediaType = 'text/html'\n\nheaders.has('Content-Type') // true\nheaders.get('Content-Type') // 'text/html'\n```\n\nIf the object still serializes to an empty string, keep the native header absent.\n\n### Cache model\n\nUse a cache keyed by lowercase header name:\n\n```ts\ntype CachedHeaderValue<value> = {\n  raw: string | null\n  revision: number\n  value: value\n}\n```\n\nOn typed getter:\n\n1. Read raw value using `Headers.prototype.get.call(this, name)`.\n2. Return cached value if raw value and revision still match.\n3. Otherwise call the existing `HeaderClass.from(raw)` method.\n4. Wrap the parsed object in a mutation-observing proxy.\n5. Store it in the cache.\n\n`set`, `append`, and `delete` should increment a revision and invalidate relevant cache entries after delegating to native `Headers` storage.\n\n### Mutation sync\n\nParsed header objects are derived views, but mutations through current views should sync back to native storage:\n\n```ts\nheaders.contentType = 'text/html'\nheaders.contentType.charset = 'utf-8'\n\nheaders.get('Content-Type') // 'text/html; charset=utf-8'\nnew Response('', { headers }).headers.get('Content-Type') // same\n```\n\nUse descriptor-level mutation metadata where possible:\n\n- direct property writes sync after assignment\n- known mutator methods sync after the method call\n- known nested arrays/objects sync via deep observation for supported structured header classes\n- read-only methods do not sync\n\nExamples that should sync:\n\n```ts\nheaders.accept.set('text/html')\nheaders.vary.add('accept-encoding')\nheaders.range.ranges.push({ start: 0, end: 99 })\nheaders.range.ranges[0].end = 199\nheaders.ifMatch.tags.push('abc')\nheaders.setCookie[0].secure = true\n```\n\nImportant implementation detail: many header value classes use `#private` fields. Proxy traps must bind methods to the original target object so private field access works:\n\n```ts\nget(target, prop, receiver) {\n  let value = Reflect.get(target, prop, target)\n  return typeof value === 'function' ? value.bind(target) : value\n}\n```\n\nAvoid calling the sync callback for read-only methods such as `toString()`, `get()`, `has()`, `accepts()`, `matches()`, `canSatisfy()`, `normalize()`, `entries()`, `keys()`, `values()`, `forEach()`, and iterator methods.\n\n### Stale object protection\n\nA typed object returned earlier must not overwrite newer native state after the same header was changed through `set`, `append`, `delete`, or a property setter.\n\nExample:\n\n```ts\nlet headers = new SuperHeaders({ 'Content-Type': 'text/html' })\nlet oldContentType = headers.contentType\n\nheaders.set('Content-Type', 'application/json')\noldContentType.charset = 'utf-8'\n\nheaders.get('Content-Type') // 'application/json'\n```\n\nUse a per-header revision token captured by the proxy. The proxy should sync only if its captured token still matches the current revision. If it does not match, mutation of the stale object is a silent no-op with respect to the `SuperHeaders` instance.\n\n### Standard method overrides\n\nOverrides should be minimal:\n\n```ts\noverride set(name: string, value: string): void {\n  Headers.prototype.set.call(this, name, value)\n  this.#invalidate(name)\n}\n\noverride append(name: string, value: string): void {\n  Headers.prototype.append.call(this, name, value)\n  this.#invalidate(name)\n}\n\noverride delete(name: string): void {\n  Headers.prototype.delete.call(this, name)\n  this.#invalidate(name)\n}\n```\n\nIf `getSetCookie()` needs an override, preserve native semantics and only add typed cache coordination.\n\n### Descriptor table and type surface\n\nKeep implementation compact with internal descriptor tables, but keep public accessor types explicit through declaration merging or an equivalent type-safe surface.\n\nPossible runtime descriptor shape:\n\n```ts\ninterface HeaderDescriptor<value, init> {\n  property: string\n  name: string\n  kind: 'object' | 'string' | 'number' | 'date' | 'set-cookie'\n  from?: (value: string | init | null) => value\n  mutatingMethods?: readonly string[]\n}\n```\n\nPossible TypeScript surface:\n\n```ts\nexport interface SuperHeaders extends SuperHeadersAccessors {}\n\ninterface SuperHeadersAccessors {\n  contentType: ContentType\n  cacheControl: CacheControl\n  setCookie: SetCookie[]\n  age: number | null\n  lastModified: Date | null\n  location: string | null\n}\n```\n\nThe implementing code can use `Object.defineProperties()` from descriptors for runtime accessors while TypeScript gets the precise interface. Avoid a public `[key: string]: unknown` or similar index signature.\n\nUse camel-case property names based on HTTP header names, e.g. `contentType`, `lastModified`, `userAgent`, `wwwAuthenticate`, `etag`.\n\n### Header coverage\n\nSupport at least the old `SuperHeaders` property list:\n\n- Structured object headers: `accept`, `acceptEncoding`, `acceptLanguage`, `cacheControl`, `contentDisposition`, `contentRange`, `contentType`, `cookie`, `ifMatch`, `ifNoneMatch`, `ifRange`, `range`, `vary`\n- Plain string headers: `acceptRanges`, `allow`, `connection`, `contentEncoding`, `contentLanguage`, `etag`, `host`, `location`, `referer`\n- Numeric headers: `age`, `contentLength`\n- Date headers: `date`, `expires`, `ifModifiedSince`, `ifUnmodifiedSince`, `lastModified`\n- Multi-value special case: `setCookie`\n\nAlso add scalar accessors for other known HTTP headers where the package does not yet have a structured parser. These should be simple string/number/date accessors as appropriate, defined through the same descriptor system. Do not add a separate handwritten getter/setter implementation per header.\n\n`etag` should preserve the old behavior of quoting plain entity tags while leaving already quoted or weak tags intact.\n\n### Set-Cookie special handling\n\n`Set-Cookie` cannot be treated like ordinary comma-combined headers. Requirements:\n\n- `headers.setCookie` returns a `SetCookie[]`.\n- `headers.setCookie = 'session=abc'` sets one cookie.\n- `headers.setCookie = { name: 'session', value: 'abc' }` works.\n- `headers.setCookie = [{ name: 'session', value: 'abc' }]` works.\n- `headers.setCookie = ['a=1', 'b=2']` works.\n- `headers.setCookie.push({ name: 'theme', value: 'dark' })` syncs to native storage.\n- `headers.setCookie[0].secure = true` syncs to native storage.\n- `headers.append('Set-Cookie', 'b=2')` preserves multiple values.\n- `headers.getSetCookie()` returns separate cookie strings.\n- `headers.get('Set-Cookie')` should follow the runtime's native `Headers` behavior.\n\nWhen syncing a `setCookie` array proxy, delete native `Set-Cookie` values and append each serialized cookie separately.\n\n## Public API sketch\n\n```ts\nimport Headers, { SuperHeaders } from '@remix-run/headers'\n\nlet headers = new Headers(request.headers)\nheaders instanceof Headers // true\nheaders instanceof SuperHeaders // true\n\nheaders.contentType = { mediaType: 'text/html', charset: 'utf-8' }\nheaders.contentType.charset = 'iso-8859-1'\n\nheaders.cacheControl = { public: true, maxAge: 3600 }\nheaders.cacheControl.maxAge = 60\n\nheaders.setCookie = { name: 'session', value: 'abc', httpOnly: true }\nheaders.setCookie.push({ name: 'theme', value: 'dark', path: '/' })\n\nnew Response('', { headers }).headers.get('Content-Type') // current value\n```\n\n## Validation criteria\n\nAdd tests in `packages/headers` covering at least:\n\n1. `new SuperHeaders() instanceof Headers` and `instanceof SuperHeaders` are both true.\n2. The package default export is `SuperHeaders`.\n3. `new Response('', { headers: new SuperHeaders({ 'X-Test': 'yes' }) }).headers.get('X-Test') === 'yes'` in Node and Bun.\n4. Constructor accepts no args, `Headers`, iterable pairs, plain header-name objects, and property initializer objects.\n5. Constructor does not accept or parse a raw whole-header string. Use `parse()` for raw strings.\n6. Typed getter access is lazy: constructor and standard `get`/`has`/iteration should not parse typed values. Use implementation-specific or test-only instrumentation if needed.\n7. Accessing an absent typed getter returns an empty object but does not make `has()` true and does not add an entry to iteration/stringification.\n8. Mutating an absent typed getter creates the native header when it serializes to a non-empty string.\n9. String property setters update native storage without requiring a typed parse.\n10. Object property setters serialize to native storage correctly.\n11. Null/undefined property setters delete the native header.\n12. Mutating current typed object properties syncs to `headers.get()` and to `new Response('', { headers }).headers`.\n13. Known mutator methods sync: `accept.set/delete/clear`, `acceptEncoding.set/delete/clear`, `acceptLanguage.set/delete/clear`, `cookie.set/delete/clear`, `vary.add/delete/clear`.\n14. Nested object/array mutations sync: `ifMatch.tags.push(...)`, `ifNoneMatch.tags.push(...)`, `range.ranges.push(...)`, `range.ranges[0].end = ...`.\n15. Standard `set`, `append`, and `delete` invalidate typed caches.\n16. Stale typed object mutations silently no-op with respect to `SuperHeaders` and cannot overwrite newer native values after invalidation.\n17. `Set-Cookie` preserves multiple values and syncs property mutations, push, index assignment, append, set, and delete.\n18. Native `Headers` iteration semantics are preserved.\n19. Raw stringification continues to use `stringify(headers)`.\n20. Behavior passes under Node and Bun using the existing package scripts: `pnpm --filter @remix-run/headers test` and `pnpm --filter @remix-run/headers test:bun`.\n21. Typecheck verifies precise public setter/getter types: `pnpm --filter @remix-run/headers typecheck`.\n22. README examples document the restored API.\n23. A change file is added under `packages/headers/.changes`.\n\n## Implementation notes\n\n- Put the implementation in `packages/headers/src/lib/super-headers.ts` and export it from `packages/headers/src/index.ts`.\n- Reuse the existing header value classes and their `.from()` methods.\n- Prefer descriptor-driven helpers over per-header handwritten implementations.\n- If adding a deep proxy helper, keep it internal to `packages/headers/src/lib`.\n- Be careful with method binding for proxied instances that use `#private` fields.\n- Avoid `any` in public types. Internal proxy helpers may need carefully isolated `unknown`/generic handling.\n- Follow repo conventions: `.ts` extensions in imports, `let` for locals, `const` for module-level constants, no semicolons, single quotes.\n- Use the `write-tests`, `write-readme`, and `make-change-file` skills when implementing this in the Remix repo.\n\n## Completion criteria\n\nThis issue is complete when `@remix-run/headers` exports a standards-compliant `SuperHeaders` class as both a named and default export, restores lazy typed property accessors backed by native `Headers` storage, supports property initializer objects, keeps mutations synchronized without stale object overwrites, passes Node and Bun package tests, and includes matching docs and release notes.","reactions":{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/remix-run/remix/issues/11339/reactions","total_count":0,"+1":0,"-1":0,"laugh":0,"hooray":0,"confused":0,"heart":0,"rocket":0,"eyes":0},"timeline_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/remix-run/remix/issues/11339/timeline","performed_via_github_app":{"id":1144995,"client_id":"Iv23liVemv8A9if9v0F2","slug":"chatgpt-codex-connector","node_id":"A_kwHOAOQ6Gs4AEXij","owner":{"login":"openai","id":14957082,"node_id":"MDEyOk9yZ2FuaXphdGlvbjE0OTU3MDgy","avatar_url":"https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/14957082?v=4","gravatar_id":"","url":"https://api.github.com/users/openai","html_url":"https://github.com/openai","followers_url":"https://api.github.com/users/openai/followers","following_url":"https://api.github.com/users/openai/following{/other_user}","gists_url":"https://api.github.com/users/openai/gists{/gist_id}","starred_url":"https://api.github.com/users/openai/starred{/owner}{/repo}","subscriptions_url":"https://api.github.com/users/openai/subscriptions","organizations_url":"https://api.github.com/users/openai/orgs","repos_url":"https://api.github.com/users/openai/repos","events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/openai/events{/privacy}","received_events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/openai/received_events","type":"Organization","user_view_type":"public","site_admin":false},"name":"ChatGPT Codex Con